ef=ES%2FI027580%2F1"><gtr:id>A3AF194F-E537-4014-A293-D5FD5FBE41AB</gtr:id><gtr:title>Company births and deaths: investigating the role of taxation</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/I027580/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This research project aims to shed new light on the impact of corporation tax on the creation and destruction of new companies, and on the behaviour of small companies. We will exploit three UK tax reforms between 1999 and 2006: the rate of corporation tax faced by small companies was reduced from 20 per cent to 10 per cent, then to zero, before being raised again to 19 per cent. We will exploit confidential, newly available, data from the HMRC Datalab on the corporation tax assessments of the universe of UK companies.&lt;br />&lt;br />A substantial number of new companies were created around the period of the low rate of tax. We aim to identify the role of taxation in inducing these company births, as well as the also substantial number of company dissolutions. We will compare the new companies with existing companies. In particular, the incentive for unincorporated firms to incorporate differs across different levels of profit: we aim to identify the extent to which new companies simply took advantage of the low starting rate. We will also investigate whether the lower starting rate induced a higher rate of corporate investment.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2012-10-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2011-03-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>83580</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>The elasticity of corporate taxable income : new evidence from UK tax records</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an activity, workshop or similar</gtr:form><gtr:id>ECE61805-D64B-45A8-86DD-E3029D0B8EBA</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Presented at event titled 'Design and impact of tax reform'. We use the population of UK corporation tax returns between 2001 and 2008 to estimate the elasticity of corporate taxable income with respect to the statutory corporation tax rate. We do so by analysing bunching in the distribution of taxable income at two kinks in the marginal rate schedule. We find a relatively small elasticity of between 0.14 and 0.18 for companies with profits around the &amp;pound; 300k kink and a small marginal deadweight cost of 8% of the revenue that would have been generated by a marginal increase in tax, ignoring behavioural responses. We find a much higher elasticity of between 0.54 and 0.57 for companies around the &amp;pound;10k kink. By matching the corporate tax return data with accounting records and analysing joint bunching in the corporate and personal tax system, we decompose the overall elasticity of corporate taxable income into two parts: an elasticity of total income with respect to the net of tax rate of between 0.2 and 0.3, and an elasticity of the share of income taken as profit with respect to the difference between the personal and corporate tax rates of between 0.04 and 0.07. With these estimated elasticities, we find that the marginal deadweight cost of the tax around &amp;pound;10k is around 25% of the increase in tax revenue, absent any behavioural responses.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-4003325657.9221472abb6128</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>The elasticity of corporate taxable income: new evidence from UK tax record</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an activity, workshop or similar</gtr:form><gtr:id>932878A0-308B-4A80-94B6-A7818D3657